  "query": "What are the documented outcomes of providing artificial non-food resources like nesting sites and water sources for primates?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on documented studies, providing artificial non-food resources for primates shows mixed outcomes for survival and population success. For artificial nesting sites and sleeping platforms, one before-and-after study in Brazil found that a translocated lion tamarin population declined after artificial nest boxes were provided alongside other interventions (Action 1530). Another study in Brazil found that a majority of reintroduced golden lion tamarins died seven years after artificial nest boxes were provided alongside other interventions (Action 1530). However, a before-and-after study in Gabon found that a majority of juvenile western lowland gorillas survived for at least seven years after nesting platforms were provided alongside other interventions (Action 1530).\n\nFor artificial water sources, documented outcomes varied by species and location. A before-and-after trial in Brazil found that a minority of reintroduced golden lion tamarins survived over seven years when provided with supplementary water alongside other interventions (Action 1531). A before-and-after study in Madagascar found that a minority of reintroduced black-and-white ruffed lemurs survived for five years despite being provided with supplementary water alongside other interventions (Action 1531). A before-and-after study in South Africa found that a minority of vervet monkeys survived for 10 months when provided with supplementary water alongside other interventions (Action 1531). In contrast, a before-and-after study in Gabon found that a majority of western lowland gorillas survived for at least nine months while being provided with supplementary water alongside other interventions (Action 1531).",
