{"query": "What is the evidence for relocating 'problem' primates versus relocating primates from residential areas for conservation?", "summary": "The evidence for relocating 'problem' primates shows mixed outcomes. For removing and relocating 'problem' animals, one study in India found that 'problem' rhesus monkeys that were translocated alongside other interventions survived and remained at release sites for at least four years (action 1422). One study in Kenya found that after 16 years, most crop-raiding olive baboons that were translocated from farmland, alongside other interventions, had survived and had similar survival rates compared to non-translocated populations (action 1422). One study in the Republic of Congo and Gaboon found that 84% of 'problem' western lowland gorillas that were relocated alongside other interventions survived for at least four years (action 1422).

However, broader evidence on translocating problem mammals shows concerning patterns. Six studies found that grizzly bears translocated away from conflict situations had lower survival rates than non-translocated bears, fewer than half of black bears translocated from conflict situations survived after one year, and most Amur tigers translocated after attacking dogs or people did not survive for a year after release (action 2336). Additionally, five studies found that brown/grizzly or black bears translocated away from residential areas often returned to their original capture location and/or continued to cause nuisance, with most returning to their capture area in some cases (action 2336). One study found that leopards translocated away from human-dominated areas attacked more humans and livestock than before translocation (action 2336).

For relocating primates to non-residential areas specifically for conservation purposes, no evidence was found for the effects of this action on primate populations (action 1423). Similarly, no evidence was found for preventing gene contamination by alien primate species through translocation (action 1536). One study found that translocated crop-raiding African elephants had lower survival rates than non-translocated elephants (action 2485).", "action_ids": ["1422","1423","1536","2336","2485"]}

