{"query": "What are the comparative outcomes of providing primates with continuous supplementary food versus providing it only during scarce periods or for a limited time?", "summary": "Based on the available evidence, different supplementary feeding strategies for primates show varying outcomes. Continuous supplementary feeding shows mixed results: two studies in China and The Gambia found population increases after regular provision of supplementary food, while two studies in Thailand and Malaysia found population declines (Action 1526). Three studies in Brazil, South Africa, and Indonesia found that the majority of primates survived with continuous feeding, and one study in Liberia found that the majority of introduced chimpanzees survived for at least one year (Action 1526). However, one controlled study in Madagascar found that continuously fed black-and-white ruffed lemurs showed different diets compared to wild groups (Action 1526). 

Feeding during resource scarce periods only appears to show more positive outcomes: studies found that the majority of chimpanzees in the Republic of Congo survived for at least five years, wild olive baboons in Kenya survived for at least 17 years after drought period feeding, and black-and-white ruffed lemurs in Madagascar maintained diets similar to wild individuals (Action 1527).

Limited-time feeding strategies show variable results: one study in Tanzania found population increases after two months of supplementary feeding following reintroduction, while one study in Brazil found population decline after one year of feeding (Action 1528). Four studies found that only a minority of reintroduced primates survived after limited supplementary feeding, though three studies in Gabon, South Africa and Vietnam found that a majority of primates survived reintroduction with supplementary feeding (Action 1528). Additionally, one controlled study in Japan found that Japanese macaque populations declined in size and productivity after limiting and then prohibiting food provisioning (Action 1502).", "action_ids": ["1526","1527","1528","1502"]}

